      <header>
        <h1 class="header">txtorg</h1>
        <p class="header">Software for preprocessing textual data in multiple languages for textual analysis. </p>

        <ul>
          <li class="download"><a class="buttons" href="https://github.com/ChristopherLucas/txtorg/zipball/master">Download ZIP</a></li>
          <li class="download"><a class="buttons" href="https://github.com/ChristopherLucas/txtorg/tarball/master">Download TAR</a></li>
          <li><a class="buttons github" href="https://github.com/ChristopherLucas/txtorg">View On GitHub</a></li>
        </ul>

        <p class="header">Produced by <a href="http://www.christopherlucas.org/">Christopher Lucas</a>, <a href="http://cns.bu.edu/~storer/">Alex Storer</a>, and <a href="http://scholar.harvard.edu/dtingley">Dustin Tingley</a>. Thanks to Sam Brotherton for work on earlier versions. </p>

	<p class="header"> Send questions and suggestions to <a href="mailto:lucas.christopherd@gmail.com">Christopher Lucas</a>.</p>

	<p class="header"> Cite: <a href="cite/bibtex.tex">BibTeX</a> | Endnote </p>

      </header>
      <section>
        <h1>
	  <a name="linux-installation" class="anchor" href="#linux-installation"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Linux installation</h1>
	<p>If you are using a Linux distribution, the installation process is fairly straightforward (isn't this why we're using Linux, after all?). 
First, download PyLucene 3.6.2 <a href ="http://lucene.apache.org/pylucene/install.html">here</a> (any version 3 release will do). 
	  From a shell, navigate to the directory in which you saved the tarball. Then, install openjdk, Apache Ant, the gnu c++ compiler, python dev, 
	  and PyLucene. Then, download and install txtorg as you would any other Python package. These steps are shown in the code block below for 
	  Debian-like distros. If your distro uses the RPM package manager, we trust that you know this and know what you need to change in the instructions 
	  below. If not, email <a href="mailto:lucas.christopherd@gmail.com">Christopher</a>. Also note that if you're using a 32-bit machine, you must edit the 
	  setup.py file such that it points to the right directory in which 
	you're JDK is installed (the default path includes a folder containing the processor and assumes 64-bit).</p>

<pre><code>$ cd this_is_where/I_saved_my_tarball
$ tar -zxvf pylucene-[PyLucene Version Here]-src.tar.gz
$ sudo apt-get install openjdk-7-jdk
$ sudo apt-get install ant
$ sudo apt-get install g++
$ sudo apt-get install python-dev
$ cd pylucene-4.5.1-1/jcc
$ sudo python setup.py build
$ sudo python setup.py build
$ cd ..
</code></pre>

	<p>Next, you need to edit the Makefile by uncommenting the section of code shown in the block below.</p>

<pre><code># Linux (Ubuntu 11.10 64-bit, Python 2.7.2, OpenJDK 1.7, setuptools 0.6.16)
# Be sure to also set JDK['linux2'] in jcc's setup.py to the JAVA_HOME value
# used below for ANT (and rebuild jcc after changing it).
PREFIX_PYTHON=/usr
ANT=JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-7-openjdk-i386 /usr/bin/ant
PYTHON=$(PREFIX_PYTHON)/bin/python
JCC=$(PYTHON) -m jcc --shared
NUM_FILES=4	    
</code></pre>

<p>Back in the terminal, finish the installation process by issuing the following commands.</p>

<pre><code>$ make
$ sudo make install
$ cd /where/I/saved/the/txtorg/tarball
$ tar -zxvf ChristopherLucas-txtorg-303111d.tar.gz
$ cd ChristopherLucas-txtorg-303111d
$ sudo python setup.py build
$ sudo python setup.py install
</code></pre>

